utting Down the Streets is the first book to conceptualize the social control of dissent in the era of alterglobalization. Based on direct observation of more than 20 global summits, the book demonstrates that social control is not only global, but also preemptive, and that it relegates dissent to the realm of criminality. The charge is insurrection, but the accused have no weapons. The authors document in detail how social control forecloses the spaces through which social movements nurture the development of dissent and effect disruptive challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-globalization movement. 0aGlobalizationxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical violence. 0aSocial control. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh1 aScholl, Christian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStarr, Amory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814740996.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814738351zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814738351/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA